# CLAUDE.md

This file provides guidance to Claude Code (claude.ai/code) when working with code in this repository.

## What This Is

A CISSP exam study environment built entirely on Claude Code skills and commands. There is no application code — the project is a structured set of reference files, progress logs, and Claude Code skills that together form an adaptive tutoring system.

## Student Profile

- (X years) IT experience
- Strong in: (list your primary skills — e.g., networking, development, sysadmin, cloud, security, etc.)
- Expert in: (list tools/platforms you know well — e.g., AWS, Kubernetes, Linux, Windows Server, etc.)
- Background: (any non-IT background that informs how you think — e.g., finance, healthcare, law enforcement, engineering, etc.)
- NOT a programmer / IS a programmer (pick one — affects how Domain 8 is taught)
- Has NOT yet taken the CISSP exam (no score breakdown available)
- Learns best through analogies mapped to existing expertise
- Does NOT want generic textbook explanations
- Analogy preferences: (list analogy types you DO NOT want — e.g., "no gaming analogies", "no sports analogies")

> **Customize this section!** The tutor, comprehension, and exam skills all read this
> profile to tailor explanations. The more specific you are, the better the analogies.
> Update the analogy-map.md file to match your background once you've filled this in.

## Architecture

### Data Flow

```
/reference/*.md  ←  ground truth (skills READ these before every response)
       ↑
       |  /promote (human review gate)
       |
/reference/pending-review.md  ←  staged additions (skills WRITE here)
       ↑
       |
  Skills (tutor, research, validator)
       |
       ↓
/progress/*.md   ←  quiz scores and weekly reviews (exam skill appends here)
```

Skills never write directly to reference files. New definitions, traps, and framework
references are staged in `pending-review.md` with source attribution. The student
reviews and promotes entries via `/promote`.

### Commands → Skills

Slash commands (`.claude/commands/`) are thin wrappers that activate skills (`.claude/skills/`). Each command reads `$ARGUMENTS` from the user and delegates to the appropriate skill:

| Command | Activates Skill | Model |
|---|---|---|
| `/study [topic]` | cissp-tutor | Opus 4.6 |
| `/research [topic]` | cissp-research | Sonnet 4.6 (with web search) |
| `/quiz [topic\|20\|full]` | cissp-exam | Haiku 4.5 |
| `/rapid-fire [topic]` | cissp-exam (rapid-fire mode) | Haiku 4.5 |
| `/validate [claim]` | cissp-validator | Opus 4.6 |
| `/promote` | (no skill — review pending additions) | — |
| `/review` | (no skill — direct analysis) | — |

The comprehension skill (`cissp-comprehension`, Sonnet 4.6) is triggered conversationally by "Challenge me on [concept]" rather than a slash command.

### Reference Files (Ground Truth)

All files in `/reference/` are **authoritative**. When training data conflicts with a reference file, the file wins. Skills must read these before responding:

- `cissp-glossary.md` — (ISC)² definitions organized by domain
- `cissp-domains.md` — 8 domains with subtopics, key concepts, and applicable frameworks
- `exam-traps.md` — Known exam traps and common misconceptions
- `analogy-map.md` — Analogy mappings for all 8 domains (customize to student background)
- `frameworks-map.md` — NIST, ISO, OWASP, GDPR, HIPAA, SOX, PCI DSS, FIPS with domain relevance

Skills that discover new definitions, traps, or framework references stage them in `pending-review.md` with source attribution. They do NOT write directly to authoritative reference files. The student reviews and promotes staged content via `/promote`. The `/research` command also saves structured summaries to `/notes/`.

### Progress Tracking

- `/progress/daily-scores.md` — Quiz/exam scores logged by cissp-exam after grading
- `/progress/weekly-reviews.md` — Analysis appended by `/review`

Score format is documented in the files themselves. The exam skill reads past scores to weight future question sets toward weak domains.

## CISSP Exam Context

- Format: CAT (100-150 questions, adaptive), 3 hours, 700/1000 to pass
- **Tests at MANAGERIAL level** — "what should the security leader do?" not "how do you configure this?"
- Many IT veterans fail by answering with technical solutions instead of management-level thinking
- Life safety is always the top priority in any scenario

### 8 Domains (weighted)

1. Security and Risk Management (16%)
2. Asset Security (10%)
3. Security Architecture and Engineering (13%)
4. Communication and Network Security (13%)
5. Identity and Access Management (13%)
6. Security Assessment and Testing (12%)
7. Security Operations (13%)
8. Software Development Security (10%)

## Daily Workflow

```
/research [topic]     → 15 min  → updates reference files
/study [topic]        → 45-60 min → 4-part format until understanding demonstrated
"Challenge me on X"   → 15-20 min → Socratic probing, pass or back to tutor
/quiz 20              → 20 min  → graded, logged to daily-scores
/validate [claim]     → as needed → fact-check against reference files
/review               → Sundays → analyze scores, adjust plan
```

## Study Timeline

WEEK 1: Diagnostic — `/quiz full` cold, identify 3 weakest and 3 strongest domains
WEEKS 2-4: Focus on 3 weakest domains (likely: Software Dev Security if non-programmer, Risk Management if non-governance, Asset Security if ops-only)
WEEKS 5-7: Fill middle-domain gaps, heavy scenario practice
WEEKS 8-10: Full practice exams 3x/week, polish "think like a manager" mindset

Adjust timeline to actual study duration. The system adapts via `/review`.

## Validator Same-Family Limitation

The validator runs on the same model family (Anthropic) as the tutor. When validator confidence is LOW (reference files insufficient), the student should cross-validate with a non-Anthropic model (e.g., GPT 5.4, Gemini 3.1 Pro) or official (ISC)² sources.
